data.content:
Here are the two files:

**`SortableList.razor`** — generic template (`@typeparam TItem`) that renders a `<ul>` with Move Up/Down buttons per item, using `@key` for efficient diffing.

**`SortableList.razor.cs`** — `partial class` code-behind with:

- **`Items`** (`IReadOnlyList<TItem>`) — input parameter, never mutated.
- **`_items`** — internal copy, created in `OnParametersSet`.
- **`ItemTemplate`** (`RenderFragment<TItem>`) — consumer-provided template (uses `@context`).
- **`OnOrderChanged`** (`EventCallback<IReadOnlyList<TItem>>`) — fires after each swap with a read-only snapshot.
- Buttons are disabled at list boundaries.

Usage matches your example — just note the callback receives `IReadOnlyList<TItem>`:

```razor
<SortableList Items="@tasks" OnOrderChanged="HandleReorder">
    <ItemTemplate>
        <span>@context.Title</span>
    </ItemTemplate>
</SortableList>

@code {
    private List<TaskItem> tasks = new() { /* ... */ };

    private void HandleReorder(IReadOnlyList<TaskItem> updated)
    {
        tasks = updated.ToList();
    }
}
```
